@pavanab4u pointed me to this and I checked with him that adding `“applyLimitPushDown”: “false”` to query context works even for v2 impl. So, my guess is that its some bug in limit push down feature.
it looks like the code has changed since 0.10.1 so maybe its already fixed but not sure.

does anyone know if this is a known issue and fixed in latest code ?

@gianm reason for originally putting it in 0.11.0 was that some customers have been blocked on this feature for quite a while.
It is fine to target it in 0.11.1. and, we will backport this (with possibly #4815 ) and release internally in 0.11.0 as soon as its merged. Also, note that we are already testing it on our metrics cluster and did few verifications.
@gianm @dclim my only request is to prioritize this in the reviews so that it gets merged as early as possible. thanks.

@gianm Do you have time to take a look at this? We've deployed this on our acceptance cluster and it works as expected. We're now able to ingest Parquet DateTime columns. This is a nice feature because it is much cheaper to extract the datetime from this DateTime field instead of parsing it using jodatime.

Currently the parquet extension works if you don't use the DateTime field. This PR will fix the classpath so we end up with the correct Avro version 1.8.2.

Cheers, Fokko

@Fokko a few of the unit tests are failing with "java.lang.NoClassDefFoundError: org/apache/avro/io/DatumReader", see the Travis link for details: https://travis-ci.org/druid-io/druid/jobs/300659465

This may be some artifact of the tests or it may point to a real issue; maybe avro is used out of the box for something in the packages where you have excluded it.

Could you take a look into the tests please?

@kevinconaway, I'm sorry it took so long to look at this.

At any rate I have one main question first. I see you've worked on making the RealtimePlumber use a SegmentAllocator rather than come up with its own identifiers. As an alternate approach did you look at trying to make the RealtimeIndexTask use an AppenderatorDriver rather than a Plumber? The Appenderator system is a bit newer and I was hoping that it would eventually replace Plumbers. They should be just as capable. It should also reduce the need for refactoring anything outside of RealtimeIndexTask.

The main issue I was thinking of with that approach is that the on-disk directory structures aren't exactly the same, so that would affect the ability of tasks to restore. I think it should be ok if it's just one time, though. If we really felt strongly about preserving the ability to restore across the upgrade, then I guess the task could peek at its on-disk structure and migrate it if needed.

@gianm Yes, I recently encountered this problem. The exception is 

_2017-11-14 19:10:12,201- epinephelinae.GroupByMergingQueryRunnerV2: Exception with one of the sequences!
java.lang.IllegalArgumentException
        at java.nio.Buffer.limit(Buffer.java:275) ~[?:1.8.0_121]
..._

I set druid.query.groupBy.bufferGrouperInitialBuckets=2147483647, so `maxBuckets` will always be `tableArenaSize/bucketSizeWithHash`.
 In the bad case,  tableArenaSize=1717986912, bucketSizeWithHash=16.  Then there is:

```
    tableStart = tableArenaSize - maxBuckets * bucketSizeWithHash;  // tableStart = 0
    int nextBuckets = maxBuckets * 2; //nextBuckets=1717986912/16*2= 214748364
    while (true) {
      // int nextTableStart = 0 - 214748364 * 16 = 858993472. However, long nextTableStart = (long) 0 - 214748364 * 16 = -3435973824
      final int nextTableStart = tableStart - nextBuckets * bucketSizeWithHash; 

      //858993472 >  tableArenaSize / 2, but -3435973824 <  tableArenaSize / 2
      if (nextTableStart > tableArenaSize / 2) {
        tableStart = nextTableStart;
        nextBuckets = nextBuckets * 2;
      } else {
        break;
      }
    }
   ...
    bufferDup.position(tableStart);  // postition(858993472)
    bufferDup.limit(tableStart + maxBuckets * bucketSizeWithHash); // 858993472 + 1717986912 = -1717986912, limit(-1717986912) will throw the illegalArgumentException.
```

@drcrallen current etag feature is being used in some druid clusters at Oath and some users have result level caches built using the etag feature outside of Druid already.  Result level Cache hit ratio typically varies from 50% to 80% depending upon the use case.
Another major advantage of result level cache is that you cache finalized value of sketches rather than sketches themselves which take alot of space if stored inside cache.

Regarding thread used for computation, I think we should ensure that cache population activity happens inside the thread that calls ResultLevelCachingQueryRunner.run(..) (I think its gonna be the jetty thread) which should be introduced instead of changing CachingClientQueryRunner too much.
